@jwang98052 done with a first pass. Mostly fine, but a few concerns:
- Relying on the outside to reset state is potentially dangerous. If the caller forgets, then we will be in an inconsistent state. Example:

```
evaluatorManager.ResetMasterEvaluatorId();

// Will have one extra, because MasterEvaluatorId has been reset!
evaluatorManager.NumberOfFailedMappers();
```
- Non-thread safe properties can be _very_ tricky to debug.

@afchung I have addressed your comments.

I put ResetMasterEvaluatorId as private and change the code for that portion. 
The class is NotThreadSafe as we discussed earlier. We will cove more testing from Driver side.

In `Org.Apache.REEF.Common\Runtime\Evaluator\Task\TaskRuntime.cs`, there is code 

```
const Level resultLogLevel = Level.Verbose;
if (Logger.CustomLevel >= resultLogLevel && result != null && result.Length > 0)
{
    Logger.Log(resultLogLevel, "Task running result:\r\n" + System.Text.Encoding.Default.GetString(result));
}
```

This needs to be updated, as we're changing the semantics of `CustomLevel`.

```
if (result != null && result.Length > 0)
{
    Logger.Log(Level.Verbose, "Task running result:\r\n" + System.Text.Encoding.Default.GetString(result));
}
```

@wonook Thanks! However, I liked the first version better, as there was no way to misuse it from a user perspective. In  this version, some can call the `public` method `EvaluatorRequestBuilder.submit()` and trigger a nullpointer exception if no `EvaluatorRequestor` was set. The one downside of the initial version was that too much of it was `public`.

We frequently encounter this problem, as Java doesn't really have a keyword to indicate "accessible only within REEF" like C# has with the `internal` keyword. We "fix" this by using the `@Private` annotation which suggests to apps not to rely on the existence of the API marked with it.

Maybe go back to the first version and mark the `public` parts of the API that shouldn't be public with `@Private`?
